  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening voice and accountability on public health and social rights in Natal and S&#xE3;o Paulo</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This 6-month project, part of the Economic Justice Programme, aims to increase access to health services by poor and marginalised sectors of the population in Natal and S&#xE3;o Paulo. Following the success of a pilot in Natal in 2014, it is to be extended to two locations in S&#xE3;o Paulo: Alvarenga, and Graja&#xFA;.

During the first semester of 2015, the project will pilot two social rights and health laboratories in S&#xE3;o Paulo, as well as continuing the work in Natal. It will support the capacity of 300 local pastoral and health agents (200 in Natal and 100 in S&#xE3;o Paulo; 65% of them women) to develop proposals, monitor health policies and strengthen public participation in health councils and electoral debates for greater social accountability and policy commitments. This will provide grounded evidence to support national level advocacy on health and social protection by the EJP and CSO partners.
 
Funding to continue this pilot will come from Brazil CGF. It will be a bridge between the end of the initial first year pilot in Natal, and the start of a new recently approved EC funded programme in the three locations and Brasilia in July 2015. It will be coordinated and managed by an existing EJP partner, Grito dos Excluidos, and implemented with Pastoral da Saude, a network of the Brazilian Bishops&#x2019; Conference.</narrative>
  </description>
